\lang english
6.
 Policy Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.1 Boundary Protection and Architecture
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Network Administrator shall monitor and control communications at the external managed interfaces and at key internal managed interfaces of County information systems,
 consistent with CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section SC-7 (Boundary Protection).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Managed Interfaces
\series default
:
 The Network Administrator shall route connections to external networks (Internet) or external information systems only through managed interfaces such as firewalls,
 proxies,
 and gateways arranged in accordance with the County security architecture.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Deny-by-Default
\series default
:
 The Network Administrator shall configure boundary protection devices to deny all inbound and outbound traffic by default,
 allowing only those services and ports explicitly authorized by the IT Director (as LASO) for documented business need.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Split Tunneling Prohibition
\series default
:
 The Systems Administrator shall configure remote access mechanisms to disable split tunneling such that all network traffic from the remote device routes through the County's managed boundary protection devices for inspection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Demilitarized Zone Implementation
\series default
:
 The Network Administrator shall locate publicly accessible system components such as web servers in a Demilitarized Zone (DMZ),
 physically or logically separated from internal organizational networks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Denial of Service
\series default
:
 The Network Administrator shall configure boundary devices to detect and mitigate denial-of-service attacks through rate limiting and traffic filtering,
 consistent with CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section SC-5 (Denial-of-Service Protection).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
PII Boundary Monitoring
\series default
:
 The Network Administrator shall monitor for permitted processing of Personally Identifiable Information (PII) at external managed interfaces and at key internal boundaries,
 consistent with CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section SC-7(24) (Boundary Protection — Personally Identifiable Information).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.2 Transmission Confidentiality and Integrity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Systems Administrator shall protect the confidentiality and integrity of transmitted information,
 consistent with CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section SC-8 (Transmission Confidentiality and Integrity).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Encryption In-Transit
\series default
:
 The Systems Administrator shall encrypt CJI and Personally Identifiable Information (PII) transmitted outside a physically secure location as defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:2.13"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Physical Security and Environmental Controls Policy).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Wireless CJI
\series default
:
 The Systems Administrator shall prohibit wireless transmission of CJI unless protected by a CMVP-validated cryptographic module.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Cryptographic Standards
\series default
:
 The Systems Administrator shall use cryptographic modules validated under the NIST Cryptographic Module Validation Program (CMVP) to protect data in transit,
 with a symmetric cipher key strength of at least one hundred twenty-eight (128) bits,
 consistent with CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section SC-13 (Cryptographic Protection).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Session Authenticity
\series default
:
 The Systems Administrator shall protect the authenticity of communications sessions through Transport Layer Security (TLS) version 1.2 or higher to prevent man-in-the-middle attacks and session hijacking.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Network Disconnect
\series default
:
 The Network Administrator shall configure VPN and remote access gateway termination at the network layer in accordance with the inactivity thresholds and Criminal Justice Conveyance exemption defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:2.04"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Access Control Policy),
 consistent with CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section SC-10 (Network Disconnect).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.3 Protection of Information at Rest
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Systems Administrator shall protect the confidentiality and integrity of information at rest,
 consistent with CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section SC-28 (Protection of Information at Rest).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
CJI Encryption
\series default
:
 The Systems Administrator shall encrypt CJI stored on digital media,
 including servers,
 workstations,
 mobile devices,
 and external drives,
 outside a physically secure location using cryptographic modules validated under the NIST Cryptographic Module Validation Program (CMVP),
 with a minimum key strength of one hundred twenty-eight (128) bits.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.4 Cryptographic Key Management
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Systems Administrator shall manage cryptographic keys to secure the key lifecycle,
 consistent with CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section SC-12 (Cryptographic Key Establishment and Management).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Generation
\series default
:
 The Systems Administrator shall generate cryptographic keys using random number generators contained within CMVP-validated cryptographic modules.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Distribution
\series default
:
 The Systems Administrator shall distribute cryptographic keys via secure methods that prevent unauthorized disclosure,
 including encrypted channels.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Storage
\series default
:
 The Systems Administrator shall not store unencrypted cryptographic keys on the same system or media as the encrypted data they protect.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Destruction
\series default
:
 The Systems Administrator shall destroy or zeroize cryptographic keys immediately when they are no longer needed or when the association with the authorized user or entity is terminated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Validation Records
\series default
:
 The Systems Administrator shall retain the CMVP validation certificate number,
 validated module name,
 validated module version,
 and implementation context for each cryptographic module relied upon to satisfy this policy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.5 Collaborative Computing Devices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
To prevent unauthorized remote surveillance,
 the Systems Administrator shall configure systems to prohibit the remote activation of collaborative computing devices,
 including cameras and microphones,
 consistent with CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section SC-15 (Collaborative Computing Devices and Applications).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Indication of Use
\series default
:
 The Systems Administrator shall deploy only collaborative computing devices that provide a physical or on-screen indication of activation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Disablement
\series default
:
 All County Personnel accessing CJI via a workstation with a built-in camera or microphone shall physically cover or logically disable the device when the device is not required for the immediate task.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.6 Secure Name and Address Resolution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Network Administrator shall ensure the integrity of the Domain Name System (DNS) infrastructure supporting County information systems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Authoritative DNS
\series default
:
 The Network Administrator shall configure County-operated authoritative DNS servers to publish DNS Security Extensions (DNSSEC) origin authentication and integrity verification artifacts for County-managed zones,
 consistent with CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section SC-20 (Secure Name/Address Resolution Service (Authoritative Source)).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Forgery Protection
\series default
:
 The Network Administrator shall configure recursive resolvers to request and validate DNSSEC signatures to verify the authenticity of DNS responses,
 consistent with CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section SC-21 (Secure Name/Address Resolution Service (Recursive or Caching Resolver)).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Fault Tolerance
\series default
:
 The Network Administrator shall maintain at least two (2) geographically separated DNS servers,
 or use a redundant cloud DNS provider,
 to ensure availability,
 consistent with CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section SC-22 (Architecture and Provisioning for Name/Address Resolution Service).
\end_layout

